{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2427"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.22,0.02,0.02,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93516"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"2100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45261"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the pre-admission clinic for an elective total knee replacement scheduled next week. Three months ago, she had an anterior ST-segment elevation acute coronary syndrome due to left anterior descending artery disease and underwent percutaneous coronary intervention with a drug-eluting stent. Since then, she has made a good functional recovery and has no current chest pain or dyspnoea. Her medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications are aspirin and ticagrelor, atorvastatin, and perindopril. She does not use tobacco or alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. The electrocardiogram today shows a sinus rhythm without acute ischaemic changes. Blood tests are within reference limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proceed to surgery and continue dual antiplatelet therapy","Proceed to surgery after stopping ticagrelor for five days","Switch ticagrelor to clopidogrel and proceed to surgery","Administer platelets perioperatively and proceed to surgery","Defer surgery by at least three months"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPerioperative planning after recent coronary stent insertion for acute coronary syndrome (ACS) requires balancing bleeding risk if dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT) is continued against stent thrombosis risk if it is interrupted. Following ACS with a drug-eluting stent, guidelines recommend 6\u201312 months of DAPT. Within the first months, stopping the P2Y12 inhibitor substantially increases stent thrombosis and myocardial infarction risk. For elective procedures that typically require interrupting antiplatelets, deferring surgery is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefer surgery by at least three months\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because the knee replacement is elective and currently timed at three months after ACS stenting, a period of heightened ischaemic risk if DAPT is interrupted. Deferral to a later date, ideally closer to 6-12 months post revascularisation, allows continuation of DAPT and lowers cardiac risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed to surgery and continue dual antiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as major joint arthroplasty carries substantial bleeding risk, and continuing DAPT increases transfusion and complication risk without addressing the ischaemic risk timing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed to surgery after stopping ticagrelor for five days\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce bleeding risk but exposes this person, only three months post-ACS stent, to a high risk of perioperative stent thrombosis; elective operations should be delayed rather than interrupt DAPT at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitch ticagrelor to clopidogrel and proceed to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E does not mitigate the need for ongoing DAPT after ACS and still necessitates interruption for surgery, leaving the same stent thrombosis risk problem unaddressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister platelets perioperatively and proceed to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is unreliable, particularly with ticagrelor, which can inhibit transfused platelets; this approach does not replace appropriate surgical timing nor reduce the risk associated with interrupting DAPT.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The duration of DAPT after undergoing revascularisation for ACS depends on both the ischaemic and bleeding risk.","Stopping DAPT within the first months after stenting carries a high risk of stent thrombosis and myocardial infarction.","Platelet or coagulation factor products do not reliably reverse the antiplatelet effect and are not substitutes for appropriate surgical timing."],"references":["Brieger D, Cullen L, Briffa T, Zaman S, Scott I, Papendick C, Bardsley K, Baumann A, Bennett AS, Clark RA, Edelman JJ, Inglis SC, Kuhn L, Livori A, Redfern J, Schneider H, Stewart J, Thomas L, Wing-Lun E, Zhang L, Ho E, Matthews S; other members of the Heart Foundation Working Group. Electronic address: clinicalevidence@heartfoundation.org.au. National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Comprehensive Australian Clinical Guideline for Diagnosing and Managing Acute Coronary Syndromes 2025. Heart Lung Circ. 2025 Apr;34(4):309-397. Available from: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline?tab=0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93516"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2427"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93516"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T18:38:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T18:38:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2427"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111386"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms"